{
  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "◁For easy reference, all of the interplay conditions discussed in this section and elsewhere in the paper are collected in Figure 2.12.",
    "Accessibility and PossibilitySo far we have said nothing about the semantics of ♢ i.",
    "Since we use the classical definition ♢ i φ:= ¬□ i ¬φ, the semantics of ♢ i is derived directly from that of ¬ and □ i as follows.Fact 2.43 (Forcing ♢ i).",
    "Given a partial-state frame F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩, x ∈ S, and Y ⊆ S, define:1. x ∈ ♦ i Y iff ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃y ′: x ′ R i y ′ and ∃y ′′ ⊑ y ′: y ′′ ∈ Y.Then for any possibility model M and φ ∈ L(Φ, I),♢ i φ M = ♦ i φ M, i.e.",
    "M, x ⊩ ♢ i φ iff ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃y ′: x ′ R i y ′ and ∃y ′′ ⊑ y ′: M, y ′′ ⊩ φ (see Figure 2.13, left).For standard frames satisfying R-down as in § 2.3, these conditions simplify to: R-ruleif x ′ ⊑ x and x ′ R i y ′ ≬ z, then ∃y: xR i y ≬ z § 2.3 R-com if x ′ ⊑ x and x ′ R i y ′, then ∃y: xR i y and y ′ ⊑ y § 2.1, § 2.3 up-R if x ′ ⊑ x and x ′ R i y ′, then xR i y ′ § 2.1, § 2.3 R-down if y ′ ⊑ y and xR i y, then xR i y ′ § 2.1, § 2.3 R⇒win if xR i y, then ∀y ′ ⊑ y ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′ ∃y ′′ ≬ y ′: x ′′ R i y ′′ § 2.3 R⇒win if xR i y, then ∀y ′ ⊑ y ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′ ∃y ′′ ⊑ y ′: x ′′ R i y ′′ § 2.3R⇔winxR i y iff ∀y ′ ⊑ y ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′ ∃y ′′ ⊑ y ′: x ′′ R i y ′′ § 2.3 R-refinability if xR i y, then ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′ ∃y ′ ⊑ y: x ′′ R i y ′ § 2.3, § B.1 R-refinability + if xR i y, then ∃y ′ ⊑ y ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′ x ′′ R i y ′ § 2.3, § B.1 R-refinability ++ if xR i y, then ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′ x ′′ R i y § 2.3, § B.1 R-dense xR i y if ∀y ′ ⊑ y ∃y ′′ ⊑ y ′: xR i y ′′ § 2.3 R-max if R i (x) ̸ = ∅, then R i (x) has a maximum in ⟨S, ⊑⟩ § 4.4 R-maxe R i (x) has a maximum in ⟨S, ⊑⟩ § 4.4 R-princ R i (x) is a principal downset in ⟨S, ⊑⟩ § 4.4Figure 2.12: all of the interplay conditions relating accessibility and refinement mentioned in the paper."
  ],
